(i)  undertake social, poverty, and gender analyses in accordance with relevant ADB 
guidelines and requirements of the Government of Viet Nam; 
(ii)  assess the potential impacts of land acquisition and loss of land on affected people 
(in terms of loss of homes, loss of agricultural land, loss of other land, and loss of 
access to current income-generating activities), including impacts caused by both 
permanent and temporary acquisition; 
(iii)  identify,  review,  and  assess  the  potential  impacts  of  the  proposed  project  on 
indigenous peoples, if any;  
(iv)  review  and  assess  the  risk  of  acquiring  and/or  spreading  HIV/AIDS  and  other 
sexually transmitted diseases;  
(v)  identify and prepare socioeconomic profiles of communities affected by the project 
in  terms  of  household  sizes,  demographic  trends,  income  sources  and  levels, 
occupations,  socioeconomic  conditions,  social  service  infrastructure,  and  social 
organizations; 
(vi)  review  the  resettlement  plan  prepared  for  the  Vinh  Tan  Project,  assess  the 
cumulative  impact  of  the  entire  Vinh  Tan  power  complex,  and  ensure  that  the 
resettlement plan is prepared in accordance with ADB's Involuntary Resettlement 
Policy (1995) and related operations manual on involuntary resettlement;  
(vii)  screen all project components (port, ash pond, new access roads, power house, 
coal handling facilities, diversion channel to provide a supply of freshwater during 
construction  and  plant  operation),  including  construction  camps,  and  prepare 
resettlement plans;  
(viii)  draft the terms of reference for a social development and resettlement specialist 
who will monitor implementation of the resettlement plan; and  
(ix)  conduct  consultation  meetings  with  stakeholders,  and  prepare  a  participation, 
consultation, and disclosure strategy for the project loan in accordance with ADB’s 
Public Communications Policy (2005) in consultation with all relevant stakeholders. 

5.  Environment Specialist (international, 4 person-months). 

7.  The consultant should have at least 10 years of experience in coal-fired power generation 
projects, preferably in Southeast Asia. The consultant will  

(i)  review the environmental impact assessment (EIA) reports prepared by the Power 
Engineering Consulting Company 2 on the impacts associated with power house, 
port, coal handling facilities, ash pond, water supply system and access road during 
construction and plant operation;  
(ii)  provide EVN with specific and detailed recommendations on mitigation measures 
and air emission control technologies to ensure compliance with ADB requirements 
and international best practices; 
(iii)  prepare a detailed environmental management plan (EMP) for the Vinh Tan power 
complex and estimate the costs of implementing the EMP;  
(iv)  draft terms of reference for the consulting services to monitor and implement the 
EMP during implementation of the proposed project;  
(v)  review existing baseline studies on air quality for the proposed project; 
(vi)  collect baseline ambient air quality data;  
(vii)  review existing baseline studies on water quality parameters; 
(viii)  review existing baseline studies on noise levels and carry out additional monitoring 
in at least six locations in the vicinity of the various operations of the proposed 
project;
